dict.string: Mr Calvin Reed, please tell us what happened
Testimony Starts: About what was seen that day.
When I am trying to start to knock on a door, a man came out from another room.
This man seems a little hurry and left the door open.
I thinks it was a little weird, so I took a look at the room.
Oh, my. I saw a woman dead in the room
I was so afraid that I did not dare to enter the room.
I though I should call the police at once.
But, the phone in the room could not be used,
So I have to use the public phone nearby to call the police.
I am quite sure about the time, it was 2 pm in the afternoon.
The man escaped is the defendant, for sure.
By the way, why the phone in the room cannot be used?
Ok, sir. Because the day, the whole apartment building was out of electricity.
But, in case of no electricity, phone can still be used, isn't it?
Yes, you are right sir. But for the phone in the room, the child phone cannot be used without electicity.
So Mr Reed cannot use the child phone to call the police.
Sir, just in case. This is the record of outage for electricity.
Ok. We will add it to the item record of the court.
Mr Holmes, now you may ask question about the evidence given by Mr Reed.
Here we go, now it is your show time.
There must be some fault in the evidence.
The key point is the material evidence.
The contradiction between the given evidence and the material evidence must be somewhere.
When I am trying to start to knock on a door, a man came out from another room.
This man seems a little hurry and left the door open.
I thinks it was a little weird, so I took a look at the room.
Oh, my. I saw a woman dead in the room
I was so afraid that I did not dare to enter the room.
I though I should call the police at once.
But, the phone in the room could not be used,
So I have to use the public phone nearby to call the police.
I am quite sure about the time, it was 2 pm in the afternoon.
The man escaped is the defendant, for sure.
We have seen all the evidence, find the fault in it.
Obviously, this evidence is contradicted with this material evidence record.
Why are you showing this to me? I don't know what you are talking about.
Frank, that is not the fault. Think harder.
He just said the time was 2 pm when he saw the dead body.
However, according to the anatomical record. She was killed after 4 pm.
It's impossible to see the dead body at 2 pm.
Wonderful move, told you that there must be some faults in the evidence.
Mr Reed, please explain why you said it's 2 pm.
When I found the dead body, I heard the time
The sound is like kind of, from a TV. Maybe it's reporting the time.
But, if it was reporting time, it cannot be two hours earlier.
So I think it might be that the woman was watching video or something like that.
After I heard that, I thought it was 2 pm in the afternoon.
Is there something that is strange?
Well, Judge, I think what he said is against with this material evidence.
I can't see anything from the material related with the given evidence.
Please be careful with what you said.
Sorry, sir. I will think about the given evidence again.
The whole apartment building is out of electricity.
No matter watching TV or video, it is not possible, isn't it?
Yes, the lawyer is right, Mr Reed, why are you saying you heard the TV?
You should give the correct evidence at the very beginning.
Sorry, sir. Seeing the dead body is a big strike on me. I am very shocked.
Sorry, I made a mistake, I didn't hear the time, I watched the time.
There is a clock in the room.
Look, it is the blunt tool that the murderer use.
I think, I watched it then I know the time.
Try to find out the contradictory part of the evidence.
I know it. See this material, it is obviously telling us Mr Reed is lying.
Are you kidding me, I cannot see any reasons.
Yes, me too. Please be careful, lawyer Holmes.
He said the clock is the weapon the murdered used.
The weapon it like this, a satue of a thinker.
Which part of it is a clock?
Sorry, Judge. May I say a word?
The statue is really a clock actually, as Mr Reed said.
There is a button on the neck, if you push the button, it will report the time.
Well, that makes sense. The statue is actually a clock.
So, Mr Holmes, do you have any question with this explanation?
Well, let me think about it.
It is a clock, but if you do not have a close look in your hand, you are not able to know that it is a clock.
But Mr Reed said he didn't enter the room.
How could he know that it is a clock? That is because...
He sells that kind of clock.
That day, he entered the room.
How could he know that it is a clock? That is because...
He sell that kind of clock, so he knows that is a clock.
I am sorry, sir. Nice try. But he sells air freshener.
Yes, you are. Do you have more to say?
Because he entered the room that day.
Yes. You used the statue to hit the victim on the head.
You must happen to make the button pushed when you hit her.
Then it reported the time and you heard it.
You must be very surprised at that time.
When Mr Reed used the clock to hit the victim, the clock reported the time.
This sound left a deep impression on you.
So you remember the time very clearly.
Is he correct, Mr Reed? Did you do that?
I heard that... er I watched...
ah ah ah ah ah ah ah ah
That man, I saw him. He killed the woman. Let him die.
What the lawyer said just now is just his guessing.
He has no evidence to support that.
Lawyer Holmes, could you please prove that Mr Reed heard the this clock.
Ok, it is really easy. We could simply
Ok, it is really easy. We could simply
Ask the neighbour, so we will know it.
There must be someone who heard the ring of the clock.
Sorry my dear Holmes, we have already asked neighbours.
When the case happened, nobody near was at home.
Oh, so you cannot prove it by doing this, Mr Holmes.
Let's try the clock right here and we will see.
Mr Wallace, would you please tell me,
what time is it right now?
So that is to say, this clock is 2 hours slower.
It is the same situation with that in the murdering room.
What do you say, Mr Reed?
Ha ha ha. You missed something.
Was this clock also 2 hours slower on that day?
If you can't prove this, then what you said just now does not mean anything.
(...... How could this thing be proved!)
Mr Holmes, it seems that you cannot prove this, right?
If so, as Mr Reed said, you cannot prove that he is the murderer.
So, we should stop for here.
(Shit! ... ...Calvin this bastard! I am almost there)
We cannot give up here, Frank. Think harder.
Instead of proving that the clock was 2 hours slower that day.
Try to think why it was 2 hours slower.
Oh, that makes sense, Jenny. Well, let me think about it.
So do you have anything to say about that, Lawyer Holmes?
Well, sir. I think I am close to it.
There is no way to prove that.......
Yes, sir. I can. I have an evidence to show this.
So then, please show it to me right now. Why the clock is slower?
It is this. This is telling us that the clock was also 2 hours slower that day.
Are you serious, Mr Holmes? I don't think it tells us anything.
Told you, you can't prove it.
The victim got back from US the day before the murder happened.
The time difference between New York and Tokyo is 14 hours.
4 pm in Tokyo, is 2 am in New York.
It is exactly 2 hours ealier than the real time.
The victim just got back the day before, she hadn't changed it to the right time.
So you heard it's 2 o'clock, but it's actually 4 o'clock.
So Mr Murderer, what else do you want to say?
So, as we can see. The truth is found out with the help of Mr Holmes.
Yes, sir. He has been arrested for murdering.
Good. Lawyer Holmes, you made a good job.
Thanks for your help to let us know the truth.
Ok, now the court is closed.
Calvin Reed, is a theft, who steals things from apartment when the host is not at home.
He pretends to be selling air freshener, which make it convenient to know who is not at home.
That day, Tom Bird went to that apartment, but nobody was at home.
After Tom left, he broke into that apartment.
When he was looking for some expensive things, the victim came back.
He was very afraid, in a hurry, he picked up the statue of thinker nearby.
